ransitions in Central and Eastern Europe -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the breakdown of socialism in Central and Eastern Europe, the role of education systems in preparing students for the "real world" changed. Though young people were freed from coercive state institutions, the shift to capitalism made the transition from school to work much more precarious and increased inequality in early career outcomes. This volume provides the first large-scale analysis of the impact social transformation has had on young people in their transition from school to work in Central and Eastern European countries. Written by local experts, the book examines the process for those entering the workforce under socialism, during the turbulent transformation years, in the early 2000s, and today. It considers both the risks and opportunities that have emerged, and reveals how they are distributed across social groups. Only by studying these changes can we better understand the long-term impact of socialism and post-socialist transformation on the problems young people in this part of the world are facing today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLabor supplyxEffect of education onzEurope, Central. 0aLabor supplyxEffect of education onzEurope, Eastern. 0aSchool-to-work transitionzEurope, Central. 0aSchool-to-work transitionzEurope, Eastern. 0aYouthxEmploymentzEurope, Central. 0aYouthxEmploymentzEurope, Eastern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aGebel, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKogan, Irena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNoelke, Clemens, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is p